article.headline: Red Raiders beat Aztecs for second year in a row
article.linkText: Powell, Valdez help Texas Tech defeat Aztecs
article.story: SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Showing the trademark of a Bob Knight team, Texas Tech needed just a few minutes to run past Steve Fisher's San Diego State Aztecs. Kasib Powell scored 22 points and Nick Valdez added a season-high 21 points off the bench for (No. 22 ESPN/USA Today, No. 23 AP) Texas Tech, which went on a 16-4 run to open the second half and beat San Diego State 75-63 on Monday night. Texas Tech led 42-38 at halftime, then blew it open when San Diego State fell apart. The Aztecs had five turnovers within the first five minutes of the second half, including on four straight possessions, helping the Red Raiders score the first 10 points for a 52-38 lead. After Texas Tech turned three SDSU turnovers into six points in just 42 seconds, Fisher called timeout. "I told the kids at the timeout, 'You know your defense is scoring, not your offense,''' Knight said. "Our getting the lead in the second half was probably as well as we played defensively all year.'' Fisher had praised his team after it trailed just 42-38 at halftime, but then saw a totally different game unfold. "We wilted under the pressure of Texas Tech's defense,'' Fisher said. "We got beat up bad in the second half. That's an understatement and an obvious statement. At one timeout, we had seven shots and nine turnovers.'' Andre Emmett started Tech's 10-0 run when he scored off a rebound, Ross had two straight baskets and Valdez had a steal and a layup, and two free throws. San Diego State didn't make its first basket of the second half until Tony Bland hit a bank shot with 13:59 left to make it 52-40. Texas Tech continued to pile it on as the Aztecs turnovers piled up, with Emmett scoring on a dunk and a jumper, and Powell on an inside shot to make it 58-42 with 11:14 to play. The Red Raiders (10-1) head into Big 12 Conference play on a five-game winning streak. San Diego State (8-4) had its six-game winning streak snapped. It was the second straight season that Knight's Red Raiders beat Fisher's Aztecs. Knight improved to 12-6 against Fisher, with all but the most recent two games coming when they were rivals in the Big Ten, Knight at Indiana and Fisher at Michigan. Knight has won four straight against Fisher in the matchup of coaches with national championships. Valdez has started twice this season, but wasn't among the starting five Monday night. He came in just 1:19 into the game after a turnover by Ronald Ross and played the rest of the game. Valdez had 13 points in the first half. Bland scored 13 points for San Diego State and Mike Mackell had 11. San Diego State committed its 10th turnover of the second half with 11:35 to play, and had 13 over the final 20 minutes to finish with a season-high 24. Emmett, Texas Tech's leading scorer with a 22.6-point average, had 16.
